3xd.title: Information
3xd.text:
Information is a measure of how much a message grants an observer the ability to predict the world. For a formal description of what this means, see [ Information: Formalization]. Information is observer-dependent: If someone tells both of us your age, you'd learn nothing, while I'd learn how old you are.

Information is measured in [shannon shannons], which are also the units used to measure [uncertainty] and [entropy]. Given that you're about to observe a coin that certainly came up either heads or tails, one shannon is the difference between utter uncertainty about which way the coin came up, and total certainty that the coin came up heads. For details, see [measuring_information Measuring information].

# Information vs Data

The word "information" has a precise, technical meaning within the field of [3qq]. Information is not to be confused with [data], which is a measure of how many messages a communication medium can distinguish in principle. For example, a series of three ones and zeros is 3 [3p0 bits] of data, but the amount of information it carries depends on the observer. Unfortunately, in colloquial usage (and even in some texts on information theory!) the word "information" is used interchangeably with the word "data"; matters are not helped by the fact that the standard unit of information is sometimes called a "bit" (the name for the standard unit of data), despite the fact that these units are distinct. The proper name for a binary unit of information is a "shannon."

Information is closely related to data:

* An object with a [3y1] of $n$ bits can carry anywhere between 0 and $\infty$ [shannon shannons] of information (depending on the observer), but the maximum amount of information a consistent observer can [expectation _expect_] from observing the object is $n$ shannons. For details, see [+expected_info_capacity].
* The number of shannons an observer gets from an observation is equal to the number of bits in the [encoding encoding] for that observation under their [ideal_encoding]. In other words, shannons measure the number of bits of data you need to be told (using your ideal encoding) to accurately predict the upcoming observation. For details, see [+ideal_encoding] and [ Information as encoding length].

For more on the difference between information and data, see [+info_vs_data].

# Information and Entropy

[+entropy] is a measure on probability distributions which, intuitively, measures the total uncertainty of that distribution. Specifically, entropy measures the number of shannons of information that the distribution [expectation expects] to gain by being told the actual state of the world. As such, it can be interpreted as a measure of how much information the distribution says it is missing about the world. See also [ Information and entropy].
